<h1>Cauchy theorem</h1>

<p>The orbit-stabilizer theorem introduced in the last paragraph as different interesting applications. The principal is Cauchy theorem.</p>

<p><b>7.16.1. Cauchy's Theorem</b>. If <i>G</i> is a finite group of order <i>n</i> and <i>p</i> a prime that divides <i>n</i>. Then <i>G</i> contains at least one element of order <i>p</i>.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. Clearly, this statement is true for the case in which <i>G</i> has ­order 2. We must find an element <i>g &ne; e</i>, <i>g<sup>p</sup> = e</i>. We introduce a new action of the group Z/pZ (the integers with addition modulo <i>p</i>), to <i>X</i>. Let</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>X</i> = {<i>g</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>g</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>g<sub>p</sub></i>: <i>g<sub>i</sub></i> &in; <i>G</i>, for <i>i</i> = 1, ..., <i>p</i>, and <i>g</i><sub>1</sub><i>g</i><sub>2</sub> ⋅⋅⋅ <i>g<sub>p</sub> = e</i>}</p>
</div>

<p>that is, <i>X</i> is the set of all <i>ordered p</i>-tuples of elements of <i>G</i> whose product is the neutral element. We prove the theorem by applying an action of the group Z/pZ, and counting orbits. For all <i>t</i> &in; Z<sub><i>p</i></sub></p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>t</i> (<i>g</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>g</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>g<sub>p</sub></i>) := (<i>g</i><sub><i>t</i> + 1</sub>, <i>g</i><sub><i>t</i> + 2</sub>, ..., <i>g<sub><i>t</i></sub></i>)</p>
</div>

<p>which corresponds to a translation of <i>t</i> positions of the indexes and their reduction modulo <i>p</i>.</p>

<ol>
	<li><p><i>X</i> has a cardinality which is a multiple of <i>p</i>: indeed <i>g</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>g</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>g<sub>p</sub></i>: <i>g<sub>p&minus;1</sub></i> can be chosen at will in <i>G</i>, <i>i.e.</i> one of the <i>n</i> = |<i>G</i>|; <i>g<sub>p</sub></i> is determined by the relation <i>g</i><sub>1</sub><i>g</i><sub>2</sub> ⋅⋅⋅ <i>g<sub>p</sub> = e</i>. Thus there are <i>n<sup>p</i>&minus;1</sup> possible strings, which is a multiple of <i>p</i>, since <i>n</i> is.</p></li>

<li><p>Owing to the orbit stabilizer theorem:</p>

<div class = "eq">
<p>O|(<i>x</i>)| ⋅ |St<sub><i>x</i></sub>| = |<i>Z<sub>p</sub></i>|</p>
</div>
</li>

<p>the cardinality of each orbit divides <i>p</i>, then every orbit has either one or <i>p</i> strings. If all orbits with the exception (<i>e, e,..., e</i>) were made by <i>p</i> strings, made by <i>p</i>, the order of <i>X</i> could not be a multiple of <i>p</i> contradicting point 1). Thus there must exist an orbit ( not reduced to <i>e, e,..., e</i>) which contains a single element, hence containing a string  (<i>g</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>g</i><sub>2</sub>, ..., <i>g<sub>p</sub></i>) &ne;  (<i>e, e,..., e</i>) which is left fixed by every element of Z<sub><i>p</i></sub>. This implies (given the action of Z<sub><i>p</i></sub> on <i>X</i>) that  <i>g</i><sub>1</sub> = <i>g</i><sub>2</sub> = ⋅⋅⋅ = <i>g<sub>p</sub></i>, that is <i>x</i><sub>1</sub> is an element of period <i>p</i>. &emsp; □</p></li>

</ol>

<p>We've seen that given a group of order <i>n</i>, is not said that for every divisor of <i>n</i> there exists a subgroup having that as order. The theorem just proved gurantees the existence that for every <i>prime divisor</i> of the order of a group, there exists a subgroup having that divisor as order: the existence of an element with period <i>p</i> gurantees that the subgroup generated by it has order <i>p</i>.</p>

<p>We can give the following definition on <i>p</i>-groups:</p>

<p><b>7.16.2. Definition</b>. Let <i>p</i> a prime number. A finite group whose order is a power of <i>p</i> is called a <i>p</i>-group.</p>

<p><b>7.16.3. Theorem</b>. Every nontrivial <i>p</i>-group has a nontrivial center.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. Let <i>G</i> a p-group and consider its partition in conjugate classes. The cardinality of every class will be either 1 or a power of <i>p</i>. The center <i>G</i> is made by all elements that commute with every element of <i>G</i> and thus contains all classes which have only one element. If the center were trivial the order of <i>G</i> would be congruent to 1 modulo <i>p</i>, which contradicts the hypothesis that |<i>G</i>| = <i>p<sup>k</sup></i>. □</p>

<p><b>7.16.4. Theorem</b>. A group <i>G</i> of order <i>p</i><sup>2</sup> is abelian.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. For what stated in the previoud theorem, the center <i>Z</i>(<i>G</i>) is nontrivial; it possesses either <i>p</i> or <i>p</i><sup>2</sup> elements. We suppose it possesses <i>p</i> elements, letting <i>a</i> an element not in  <i>Z</i>(<i>G</i>). Then the cetralizer of <i>a</i>, C(<i>a</i>) = {<i>g</i> &in; G | <i>ga = ag</i>} is a subgroup of <i>G</i> containing properly <i>Z</i>(<i>G</i>). Then owing to Lagrange theorem, it coincides with all <i>G</i>, which is absurd because <i>a</i> should be contained in <i>Z</i>(<i>G</i>). It remains the only possibility that <i>Z</i>(<i>G</i>) has <i>p</i><sup>2</sup> elements, that is to coincide with all <i>G</i>. <i>G</i> is abelian. □</p>

<h2>Sylow theorems</h2>

<p>We know from Lagrange’s Theorem that the order of a subgroup of a finite group <i>G</i> must divide the order of <i>G</i>. A natural related question is the following: If <i>m ∈ N</i> and m divides |<i>G</i>|, does there exist a subgroup of <i>G</i> of order <i>m</i>? The answer, in general, is no. For example, <i>A</i><sub>4</sub> (of order 12) has no subgroup of order 6. However, there are circumstances in which the answer will be yes. We consider one such situation here and consider three fundamental theorems of the Norwegian mathematician Ludwig Sylow (1832–1918).</p>

<p><b>7.16.5 Definition</b>. A <i>p</i>-subgroup <i>P</i> of a finite gorup, |<i>G</i>| with the property that its cardinality is the largest power of <i>p</i> dividing |<i>G</i>| is known as Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup.</p>

<p><b>7.16.6 First Sylow theorems</b>. Let <i>G</i> a finite group whose order is <i>p<sup>a</sup> ⋅ m</i>, with <i>p</i> a prime number and <i>m</i> not divisible by <i>p</i>. Then <i>G</i> contains a subgroup of order <i>p<sup>a</sup></i>, that is a Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. Let <i>X</i> the set of all subsets of <i>G</i> having <i>p</i><sup>a</sup> elements. Consider the action of <i>G</i> on <i>X</i>  via left translation: given <i>U</i> &in; <i>X</i> and a <i>g</i> &in; G, we let <i>g</i> * <i>U</i> := <i>gU</i>. Given the cardinality of <i>X</i></p>

<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
  <mo stretchy="false">|</mo>
  <mi>X</mi>
  <mrow data-mjx-texclass="ORD">
    <mo stretchy="false">|</mo>
  </mrow>
  <mo>=</mo>
  <mrow data-mjx-texclass="ORD">
    <mrow data-mjx-texclass="OPEN">
      <mo minsize="2.047em" maxsize="2.047em">(</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mfrac linethickness="0">
      <mrow>
        <msup>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mi>a</mi>
        </msup>
        <mo>&#x22C5;</mo>
        <mi>m</mi>
      </mrow>
      <msup>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mi>a</mi>
      </msup>
    </mfrac>
    <mrow data-mjx-texclass="CLOSE">
      <mo minsize="2.047em" maxsize="2.047em">)</mo>
    </mrow>
  </mrow>
</math>

<p>which is not divisible by <i>p</i> (see <a href="exercises_sylow.html">exercise</a>), and since <i>X</i> can be partitioned into orbits, there must exist an element <i>A</i> &in; <i>X</i> such that O(<i>A</i>) has a number of elements <i>which is not a multiple of p</i>.</p>

<p>But then, from the relation</p>

<div class="eq">
<p>|O(<i>A</i>)| |St(<i>A</i>)| = |<i>G</i>|</p>
</div>

<p>it follows that |St(<i>A</i>)| must be a multiple of <i>p<sup>a</sup></i>. By definition of stabilizer and given the definition of action, letting an element <i>a</i> &in; <i>A</i> and a <i>g</i> &in; St<sub>A</sub>, it results <i>ga</i> &in; <i>A</i>, which means that the right lateral St<sub>A</sub>a is contained in <i>A</i> for all <i>a</i> &in; <i>A</i>. This implies that |St<sub>A</sub>| &le; |<i>A</i>|, that is <i>p<sup>a</sup></i>. Since St<sub>A</sub><i>a</i> has the same cardinality of St<sub>A</sub>, it follows that St<sub>A</sub> is a <i>subgroup of <i>G</i> of exactly <i>p<sup>a</sup></i> elements</i>. &emsp; □</p>

<p><b>7.16.7 Lemma</b>. If <i>K</i> is a Sylow p-subgroup of G, then so is xKx<sup>&minus;1</sup>.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. Let <i>G</i> be a group and <i>x</i> &in; <i>G</i>. <a href="group_isomorphism.html">Example 7.8.2</a> shows that the map <i>f</i> : <i>G</i> ⟶ <i>G</i> given by f(a) = xax<sup>&minus;1</sup> is an isomorphism. If <i>K</i> is a subgroup of <i>G</i>, then the image of <i>K</i> under <i>f</i> is xKx<sup>&minus;1</sup> = {<i>xkx</i><sup>&minus;1</sup> |k &in; K}. Hence, xKx<sup>&minus;1</sup> is a subgroup of <i>G</i> that is isomorphic to <i>K</i>. &emsp; □</p></p>

<p>Let <i>P</i> the set of all Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroups of <i>G</i>. <i>P</i> is not empty by the first Sylow theorem. If <i>S</i> &in; <i>P</i>, then <i>P</i> contains also all conjugates of <i>S</i>, through the elements of <i>G</i>, since they are all subgroup of the same largest order <i>p<sup>a</sup></i>. Given the orbit O(<i>S</i>), of <i>S</i> with respect to the action of <i>G</i> on <i>P</i> by conjugation, we have O(<i>S</i>) &subseteq; <i>P</i>. In addition the cardinality of O(<i>S</i>) divides <i>m</i>. Indeed, since (see <a href="normal_subgroups.html#normalizer">Proposition 7.11.13</a>):</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>St<sub>S</sub></i> = {<i>g ∈ G</i> | <i>gSg<sup>&minus;1</sup> = S</i>} = <i>N<sub>G</sub></i>(<i>S</i>) (normalizer of <i>S</i> in <i>G</i>)</p>
</div>

<p>it's clear that <i>St<sub>S</sub></i> ⊇ <i>S</i>, then |<i>St<sub>S</sub></i>| = <i>p<sup>a</sup>r</i>. The cardinality of O(<i>S</i>), then divides <i>m</i>, based on the relation |O(<i>S</i>)| |St<sub><i>S</i></sub>| = |<i>G</i>| and is relatively prime to <i>p</i>.</p>

<p>We can now give an alternative proof of Cauchy's Theorem.</p>

<p><b>Corollary 7.16.8 (Cauchy's Theorem)</b> If <i>G</i> is a finite group whose order is divisible by a prime <i>p</i>, then <i>G</i> contains an element of order <i>p</i>.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. If <i>p</i> is a prime that divides the order of a group <i>G</i>, then <i>G</i> contains a subgroup <i>K</i> of order <i>p</i> by the First Sylow theorem. Since <i>K</i> cyclic <a href="cosets.html">by Corollary 7.8.6</a> of Lagranges's Theorem, its generator is an element of order <i>p</i> in <i>G</i>.&emsp; □</p>

<p><b>7.16.8 (Second Sylow Theorem)</b>. Let <i>G</i> be a finite group with order <i>p<sup>a</sup> ⋅ m</i> and <i>p</i> a prime such that <i>m</i> is not divisible by <i>p</i>. Then any <i>p</i>-subgroup <i>H</i> of <i>G</i> is contained in a <i>p</i>-Sylow subgroup. </p>

<p><b>Proof.</b> Let <i>P</i> be the set of <i>p</i>-Sylow subgroups of <i>G</i>, and let <i>H</i> be a <i>p</i>-subgroup of <i>G</i>, and let |<i>H</i>| = <i>p<sup>s</sup></i>, <i>s &le; a</i> since a p-subgroup of <i>G</i> canno have order greater by p<sup>a</sup> by Lagrange's Theorem. Let <i>S</i> a fixed <i>p</i>-Sylow subgroup and O(<i>S</i>) its orbit under the conjugation action. Let <i>H</i> act on O(<i>S</i>): <i>hT</i> = <i>hTh</i><sup>&minus;1</sup> &forall;<i>T</i> &in; O(<i>S</i>): it's an <a href="actions_groups.html">action</a> on on O(<i>S</i>) because the conjugate of an element is still in O(<i>S</i>). O(<i>S</i>) is thus partitioned into suborbits, each one having a cardinality which divides <i>p<sup>s</sup></i>. The cardinality O(<i>S</i>) is the sum of the cardinalities of all these suborbits. Since |O(<i>S</i>)| divides <i>m</i> and is *therefore* relatively prime to <i>p</i> (for all divisors of |<i>G</i>|, being coprime to <i>p</i> is the same as dividing m: "divisor of <i>m</i>, with <i>m</i> coprime to <i>p</i>" => "divisor coprime to <i>p</i>"), there exists at least one suborbit having just one element (consider 1 + <i>p</i> + <i>p</i> + <i>p</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>p</i><sup>3</sup>, it's NOT a multiple of <i>p</i>); that is ∃<i>T</i> &in; O(<i>S</i>) such that <i>hTh</i><sup>&minus;1</sup> = <i>T</i> &emsp; &forall;<i>h</i> &in; <i>H</i>.</p>

<p>Then <i>H</i> ⊆ St<sub><i>T</i></sub> = {<i>g</i> &in; <i>G</i> | <i>gTg</i><sup>&minus;1</sup> = <i>T</i>} = N<sub><i>G</i></sub>(<i>T</i>) (normalizer of <i>T</i> in <i>G</i>). Clearly <i>T</i> ⊲̲ N<sub><i>G</i></sub>(<i>T</i>) (See <a href="normal_subgroup.html">Proposition 7.11.14</a>). We can then construct the quotient group N<sub><i>G</i></sub>(<i>T</i>)/<i>T</i> and consider the subgroup <i>HT/T</i> ⊲̲ N<sub><i>G</i></sub>(<i>T</i>)/<i>T</i>. By the <a href="group_isomorphism_theo.html">First Isomorphism Theorem</a>, <i>HT</i>/<i>T</i> ≃ <i>H</i>/<i>H</i> ∩ <i>T</i>.</p>

<p>Note that |HT/T| divides <i>m</i> and therefore relatively prime to <i>p</i>. HT/T = HT = {hT = Th | h in H}, <i>HT</i> is a subgroup of G containing T, so its order is p<sup>d</sup> k  for some k coprime to p and such that k|m with d &le; a. Now note that |<i>H</i> / <i>H</i> ∩ <i>T</i>| = |<i>H</i>| / <i>H</i> ∩ <i>T</i>| = [<i>H</i> : <i>H</i> ∩ <i>T</i>] = <i>p<sup>r</sup></i> for some <i>r</i> &ge; 0 and &le; <i>s</i> (we applied Lagrange's theorem that is |G| / |H| = (G:H) and (G:H) is the number of cosets, but this number is nothing else than |G/H|). Thus it must necessarily be |<i>H</i>/<i>H</i> ∩ <i>T</i>| = 1, that is <i>H</i> ⊆ <i>T</i>. We have so proved that every <i>p</i>-subgroup <i>H</i> is contained in a Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup of <i>G</i>. &emsp; □</p>

<p>The next Corollary shows that every Sylow p-subgroup of G can be obtained from a conjugate in the fashion of Lemma 7.16.7.</p>

<p><b>7.16.9 Corollary</b>. Any two Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroups of a finite group <i>G</i> are conjugate in <i>G</i>.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. We have to prove that O(<i>S</i>) = <i>P</i>, that is the oribit O(<i>S</i>) defined as in the first Sylow theorem, contains all Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup. Let <i>Q</i> and <i>R</i> be two <i>p</i>–Sylow subgroups of <i>G</i>. According to the theorem, there is an <i>a</i> &in; <i>G</i> such that <i>aQa</i><sup>&minus;1</sup> &subseteq; <i>R</i>. We proved in the last theorem that every <i>p</i>-subgroup <i>H</i> is contained in a conjugate <i>T</i> that is <i>H</i> &subseteq; <i>T</i>. In particular in the case of <i>H</i> Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup, it must necessarily be <i>H = T</i> since every Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup has <i>p<sup>a</sup></i> elements. &emsp; □</p>

<p><b>7.16.10 Third Sylow Theorem</b>. The number of distinct Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroups of a finite group <i>G</i> divides |<i>G</i>| = p<sup>a</sup> ⋅ m with (<i>p,m</i>) = 1 and is congruent to 1 modulo <i>p</i>.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. Let <i>P</i> be the set of all Sylow p-subgroups of <i>G</i> and <i>S</i> &in; P. Consider the action of the Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup <i>H</i> on O(<i>S</i>) by conjugation; there is only one suborbit of O(<i>S</i>) with one element; indeed if there were another suborbit with order 1, <i>H</i> would be identical to another Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup. Being the cardinality of all other suborbits a power <i>p</i><sup>k</sup> (with <i>k</i> &gt; 0), the cardinality of O(<i>S</i>) is thus conruent to 1 modulo <i>p</i>.  &emsp; □</p>

<p><b>7.16.11 Applications</b> Every subgroup of order 20 contains a normal subgroup.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. 20 = 2<sup>2</sup> * 5. The number of 5-Sylow subgroups must be a divisor of 4 that is it can be 1, 2, or 4, but it also needs to be congruent to 1 modulo 5. The only choice is therefore 1. If a Sylow <i>p</i>-subgroup in unique, this is necessarily a normal subgroup (see <a href="exercises_sylow.html">exercise</a>). &emps;■ </p>

<p>A group without normal non-trivial subgroup is said 

